  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Vomit acid, lose K+, get alkalosis; fix volume first!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Hypokalemic hypochloremic metabolic alkalosis. Prolonged vomiting from pyloric obstruction leads to significant loss of gastric acid (HCl), potassium, and fluid, resulting in this classic electrolyte and acid-base imbalance.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPyloric obstruction prevents gastric emptying, causing persistent vomiting of highly acidic gastric contents. The loss of hydrogen ions (H+) directly causes metabolic alkalosis. Concurrently, the loss of chloride ions (Cl-) leads to hypochloremia. Volume depletion stimulates the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system, leading to increased renal potassium excretion and further exacerbating hypokalemia, which is also contributed to by direct loss of potassium in gastric fluid.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hyperchloremia and metabolic acidosis are not expected; vomiting causes hypochloremia and alkalosis.\nOption B (Incorrect): Hyperkalemia is incorrect; vomiting causes hypokalemia due to gastric losses and renal compensation for volume depletion.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hyperkalemia, hyperchloremia, and metabolic acidosis are all incorrect for this clinical scenario.\nOption E (Incorrect): While hypokalemic and hypochloremic are correct, hypernatremia is not the primary or most consistent electrolyte disturbance, and metabolic acidosis is incorrect.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Disturbance | Cause in Pyloric Obstruction | Effect on Body |\n|---|---|---|\n| Metabolic Alkalosis | Loss of gastric HCl (H+ ions) | Increased blood pH, compensatory hypoventilation |\n| Hypochloremia | Loss of gastric HCl (Cl- ions) | Contributes to alkalosis, impairs renal H+ excretion |\n| Hypokalemia | Loss of gastric K+, renal K+ excretion (aldosterone, volume depletion) | Muscle weakness, arrhythmias, exacerbates alkalosis |\n| Volume Depletion | Loss of fluid from vomiting | Activates RAAS, leads to renal K+ and H+ excretion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Vomiting = lose acid, get alkalosis; lose K+, get hypokalemia; lose Cl-, get hypochloremia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn upper GI series or CT, pyloric obstruction would show a dilated stomach with retained fluid and food particles, and delayed or absent passage of contrast into the duodenum. Endoscopy would reveal the obstructing lesion (e.g., ulcer, tumor) at the pylorus.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline on the Management of Peptic Ulcer Disease (2017) recommends medical therapy for ulcer disease, but surgical intervention (e.g., pyloroplasty, gastrojejunostomy) for refractory cases or complications like obstruction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hypokalemic hyperchloremic metabolic acidosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hyperkalemic hypochloremic metabolic alkalosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hyperkalemic hyperchloremic metabolic acidosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hypokalemic hypochloremic metabolic alkalosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Hypokalemic hypernatremic hypochloremic metabolic acidosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
