  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lymphocytes: specific immunity, not phagocytosis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Lymphocytes. This question tests fundamental knowledge of immune cell functions, specifically identifying which cell type among the options is not primarily involved in phagocytosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPhagocytosis is a critical innate immune mechanism where specialized cells engulf and digest foreign particles, pathogens, or cellular debris. Neutrophils are rapid responders, crucial for bacterial clearance. Macrophages, including their specialized forms like microglial cells in the CNS and Kupffer cells in the liver, are professional phagocytes that also act as antigen-presenting cells. Lymphocytes, however, are central to adaptive immunity, mediating highly specific immune responses through T-cell receptors or B-cell antibodies, rather than through engulfment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Neutrophil polymorphonuclear leucocytes are highly phagocytic cells, essential for the acute inflammatory response and bacterial killing.\nOption C (Incorrect): Microglial cells are the resident macrophages of the central nervous system and are crucial phagocytes for immune surveillance and debris clearance in the brain.\nOption D (Incorrect): Macrophages are professional phagocytes, vital for engulfing pathogens, presenting antigens, and clearing cellular debris throughout the body.\nOption E (Incorrect): Kupffer cells are specialized macrophages located in the liver sinusoids, actively phagocytosing foreign material, bacteria, and old red blood cells.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cell Type | Primary Function | Phagocytic? |\n|---|---|---|\n| Neutrophil | Acute inflammation, bacterial clearance | Yes |\n| Lymphocyte | Adaptive immunity (specific antigen recognition) | No |\n| Macrophage | Antigen presentation, pathogen clearance, tissue repair | Yes |\n| Microglial cell | CNS immune surveillance, debris clearance | Yes |\n| Kupffer cell | Liver immune surveillance, erythrocyte recycling | Yes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Phagocytes engulf; lymphocytes target specific antigens.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn microscopy, phagocytic cells often show internalized particles or vacuoles within their cytoplasm, while lymphocytes are typically characterized by a large, dense nucleus and scant cytoplasm, lacking phagocytic inclusions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWhile no specific surgical guideline applies, fundamental immunology principles, as outlined by organizations like the American Association of Immunologists, define these cellular functions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Neutrophil polymorphonuclear leucocytes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lymphocytes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Microglial cells. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Macrophages. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Kupffer cells. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
