  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't operate on sick patients; optimize first!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, \"Previous mitral valve replacement,\" because a history of valve replacement, while indicating underlying cardiac disease, is not an absolute contraindication to major elective surgery if the patient is stable and optimized. The other options represent acute or subacute conditions that significantly increase perioperative risk and would typically necessitate postponement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA previous mitral valve replacement signifies a stable, managed cardiac condition. With appropriate preoperative cardiac evaluation, optimization of medical therapy, and careful management of anticoagulation (e.g., bridging therapy), these patients can safely undergo major elective surgery. The key is stability and optimization, not the mere presence of the prosthetic valve itself. This contrasts with acute or subacute conditions that pose immediate and significant physiological derangements or high recurrence risks.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Myocardial infarction 2 months ago is a significant risk factor. Current guidelines recommend delaying elective noncardiac surgery for at least 60 days, and often longer (3-6 months), after an MI due to increased risk of reinfarction and cardiac events.\nOption B (Incorrect): Preoperative serum potassium of 2.5 mmol/liter is severe hypokalemia. This must be corrected before elective surgery to prevent life-threatening arrhythmias, especially under general anesthesia.\nOption D (Incorrect): A resolving upper respiratory tract infection increases the risk of perioperative pulmonary complications (e.g., bronchospasm, pneumonia, atelectasis) and is generally a reason to postpone major elective surgery until symptoms have fully resolved.\nOption E (Incorrect): Stroke within 4 months before surgery carries a high risk of perioperative stroke recurrence and other neurological complications. Elective surgery is typically delayed for at least 3-6 months post-stroke.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Perioperative Risk | Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Recent MI (<6 months) | High risk of reinfarction, cardiac events | Delay surgery 60 days minimum, ideally 3-6 months |\n| Severe Hypokalemia (<3.0 mmol/L) | Arrhythmias, muscle weakness | Correct electrolyte imbalance preoperatively |\n| Recent Stroke (<6 months) | High risk of stroke recurrence, neurological complications | Delay surgery 3-6 months |\n| Resolving URI | Increased pulmonary complications (bronchospasm, pneumonia) | Postpone until symptoms fully resolved (2-4 weeks) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute or uncorrected physiological derangements are contraindications; stable chronic conditions are not.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn a patient with a previous mitral valve replacement, intraoperatively, one might hear a prosthetic valve click on auscultation or see the prosthetic valve on intraoperative transesophageal echocardiography (TEE) if performed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2014 ACC/AHA Guideline on Perioperative Cardiovascular Evaluation and Management of Patients Undergoing Noncardiac Surgery. This guideline recommends delaying elective noncardiac surgery for at least 60 days after an MI and emphasizes correction of electrolyte abnormalities.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Myocardial infarction 2 months ago. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Preoperative serum potassium of 2.5 mmol/liter in a patient on diuretic the | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Previous mitral valve replacement. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | A resolving upper respiratory tract infection. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Stroke within 4 months before surgery. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
