  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Heart muscle: The ultimate metabolic chameleon, not a glucose slave!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Cardiac Muscles. This question tests your understanding of organ-specific metabolic fuel preferences. While many tissues can utilize glucose, only a few are obligate glucose users, meaning they cannot effectively switch to other fuel sources under normal physiological conditions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCardiac muscle is highly metabolically flexible, capable of utilizing a wide range of substrates for energy production, including fatty acids (its preferred fuel), lactate, ketones, and glucose. This adaptability is crucial for maintaining continuous heart function. In contrast, tissues like red blood cells, the brain, renal medulla, and bone marrow have limited or no capacity to metabolize alternative fuels, making them critically dependent on a constant supply of glucose.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Red Blood Cells) (Incorrect): Red blood cells lack mitochondria and thus rely exclusively on anaerobic glycolysis for ATP production, making them obligate glucose users.\nOption C (Renal Medulla) (Incorrect): The renal medulla operates under hypoxic conditions and has a high metabolic rate, primarily relying on anaerobic glycolysis of glucose for energy.\nOption D (Bone Marrow) (Incorrect): Bone marrow is a highly proliferative tissue with significant energy demands for hematopoiesis, predominantly met by glucose metabolism.\nOption E (Brain) (Incorrect): Under normal conditions, the brain relies almost entirely on glucose as its energy source, as fatty acids cannot cross the blood-brain barrier effectively.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Organ/Tissue | Primary Fuel Source(s) | Obligatory Glucose User? |\n|---|---|---|\n| Red Blood Cells | Glucose (anaerobic glycolysis) | Yes |\n| Cardiac Muscles | Fatty acids, lactate, ketones, glucose | No |\n| Renal Medulla | Glucose (anaerobic glycolysis) | Yes |\n| Brain | Glucose | Yes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think 'no mitochondria' or 'hypoxic' for obligate glucose users.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question pertains to cellular metabolism and does not directly relate to imaging or intraoperative findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThis is a foundational physiology concept and is not directly addressed by specific surgical society guidelines.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Red Blood Cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cardiac Muscles | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Renal Medulla | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Bone Marrow | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Brain | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
