  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Feed glucose, save muscle.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 100 gm. Administering approximately 100 grams of glucose per day is the minimum threshold required to initiate the protein-sparing effect, thereby suppressing gluconeogenesis and minimizing protein catabolism.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWhen exogenous glucose is provided, the body shifts its primary energy source from endogenous stores (like protein via gluconeogenesis) to the administered glucose. This glucose load stimulates insulin release, which in turn inhibits hepatic glucose production (gluconeogenesis and glycogenolysis) and promotes glucose utilization by peripheral tissues. By providing a readily available energy substrate, the need to break down muscle protein for amino acids to fuel gluconeogenesis is significantly reduced, thus \"sparing\" protein.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (200 gm) (Incorrect): While 200 gm would certainly provide a protein-sparing effect, the question asks when the effect *begins* to be manifested, making 100 gm the more precise answer for the threshold.\nOption C (75 gm) (Incorrect): 75 gm of glucose is generally considered insufficient to reliably achieve a significant protein-sparing effect and fully suppress gluconeogenesis in most adults.\nOption D (300 gm) (Incorrect): 300 gm is a substantial amount of glucose, well beyond the minimum required for protein sparing, and could lead to hyperglycemia if not carefully managed.\nOption E (500 gm) (Incorrect): 500 gm is an excessive amount of glucose for initiating protein sparing and would almost certainly cause significant hyperglycemia and metabolic complications.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Glucose Amount (gm/day) | Metabolic Effect | Clinical Implication |\n|---|---|---|\n| < 75 | Minimal protein sparing | Significant gluconeogenesis, protein catabolism |\n| 100-150 | Initiates protein sparing, suppresses gluconeogenesis | Minimizes muscle breakdown, preserves lean body mass |\n| 200-300 | Provides significant caloric support | Used in total parenteral nutrition (TPN) for energy |\n| > 300 | Risk of hyperglycemia, lipogenesis | Requires careful monitoring, potential for overfeeding complications |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: 100g glucose daily starts protein sparing, halting muscle breakdown.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nN/A\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASPEN Guidelines for the Provision and Assessment of Nutrition Support Therapy in the Adult Critically Ill Patient (2016). Recommends providing adequate non-protein calories (primarily glucose) to minimize protein catabolism, with initial glucose infusion rates typically starting around 1-2 mg/kg/min, which translates to roughly 100-150g/day for an average adult.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 100 gm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 200 gm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 75 gm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 300 gm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | 500 gm | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
