  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Controlled GI entry equals clean/contaminated, Class II.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Elective upper GI surgery. This scenario perfectly represents a clean/contaminated (Class II) wound because it involves controlled entry into a viscus (the gastrointestinal tract) that contains normal bacterial flora, without significant spillage or signs of infection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSurgical wound classification is crucial for predicting infection risk and guiding prophylactic antibiotic use. A clean/contaminated (Class II) wound is defined as an operative wound in which the alimentary, respiratory, or genitourinary tract is entered under controlled conditions and without unusual contamination. While bacteria are present, the surgical technique minimizes their spread, leading to a lower infection rate than truly contaminated or dirty wounds. Elective upper GI surgery, such as a gastrectomy or esophagectomy, fits this description as the GI tract is opened in a controlled manner.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Penetrating abdominal trauma is typically a contaminated (Class III) or dirty/infected (Class IV) wound due to external contamination and potential gross spillage of bowel contents.\nOption B (Incorrect): Large tissue injury is a descriptive term for the extent of damage, not a classification based on bacterial load. It could fall into any wound class depending on the cause and environment.\nOption D (Incorrect): Enterotomy during bowel obstruction implies a high bacterial load, compromised bowel wall, and potential for significant contamination, making it a contaminated (Class III) or dirty/infected (Class IV) wound.\nOption E (Incorrect): Perforated diverticulitis involves gross spillage of infected colonic contents into the peritoneal cavity, which is a classic example of a dirty/infected (Class IV) wound.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Wound Class | Definition | Infection Rate | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Clean (Class I) | No inflammation, no entry into tracts | 1-2% | Hernia repair, thyroidectomy |\n| Clean/Contaminated (Class II) | Controlled entry into tracts | 3-7% | Elective cholecystectomy, gastrectomy |\n| Contaminated (Class III) | Gross spillage, acute inflammation | 10-15% | Open fracture, colon resection with spillage |\n| Dirty/Infected (Class IV) | Pre-existing infection, pus, perforated viscus | >25% | Abscess drainage, perforated appendicitis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Clean/Contaminated means controlled entry into a viscus with normal flora.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring elective upper GI surgery, intraoperative findings would include a controlled surgical field, careful handling of tissues, minimal spillage of gastric or intestinal contents, and healthy surrounding tissues. No specific imaging is implied by the question for this classification.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC Guidelines for the Prevention of Surgical Site Infection (2017): These guidelines provide recommendations for surgical wound classification and prophylactic antibiotic use based on the presumed bacterial load.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Penetrating abdominal trauma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Large tissue injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Elective upper GI surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Enterotomy during bowel obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Perforated diverticulitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
