  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Granulation tissue: the stoma's harmless, bloody secret.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe most likely diagnosis for intermittent bright red bleeding from a tracheostomy site two weeks post-op, which resolves without intervention and with normal coagulation, is bleeding from granulation tissue. This is a common and benign complication in the early post-operative period.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGranulation tissue is highly vascular and friable, forming as part of the normal wound healing process around the stoma. Its delicate nature makes it prone to minor trauma, such as suctioning, coughing, or movement of the tracheostomy tube, leading to intermittent bright red bleeding. The bleeding is typically self-limiting due to the small vessel size and the body's natural hemostatic mechanisms, aligning with the patient's presentation of spontaneous resolution and stable hemoglobin.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Pneumonia) (Incorrect): Pneumonia presents with respiratory symptoms like fever, cough, and purulent sputum, not primarily intermittent bright red bleeding from the stoma. Bleeding would typically be hemoptysis.\nOption B (Tracheitits) (Incorrect): While tracheitis can cause irritation and some bleeding, it's usually diffuse and less likely to manifest as intermittent, bright red, self-resolving bleeding from the stoma itself, which is more characteristic of a localized vascular source.\nOption D (Tracheoinnominate fistula) (Incorrect): A tracheoinnominate fistula is a catastrophic, life-threatening complication presenting with a sentinel bleed followed by massive, pulsatile hemorrhage. The description of intermittent bleeding that resolved without intervention and stable Hb does not fit this diagnosis.\nOption E (Bleeding from the anterior jugular vein) (Incorrect): While possible, bleeding from a major vein would likely be more continuous or significant, and less likely to be intermittent and resolve completely without intervention compared to friable granulation tissue.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Presentation | Timing | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Granulation Tissue Bleed | Intermittent, bright red, self-limiting | Early post-op (weeks) | Observation, cautery if persistent |\n| Tracheoinnominate Fistula | Sentinel bleed followed by massive hemorrhage | 1-3 weeks post-op | Immediate surgical exploration, sternotomy, ligation |\n| Stomal Infection | Erythema, purulence, pain, fever | Any time | Local wound care, antibiotics |\n| Tracheal Stenosis | Progressive dyspnea, stridor | Weeks to months post-op | Bronchoscopy, dilation, resection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Intermittent, self-resolving tracheostomy bleeding is usually granulation tissue, not TIF.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, granulation tissue appears as friable, reddish, often polypoid masses around the stoma or within the tracheal lumen near the tube tip. Intraoperatively, it can be easily identified and cauterized if necessary.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology–Head and Neck Surgery Foundation (AAO-HNSF) Clinical Practice Guideline: Tracheostomy (2013) recommends careful stoma care to minimize granulation tissue formation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pneumonia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Tracheitits | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bleeding of granulation tissue in the stoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Tracheoinnominate fistula | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Bleeding from the anterior jugular vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
