  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 0.5 mL/kg/hour: The golden rule for kidney's happy hour!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C, 35 ml/hour, is the correct answer. This represents the minimum acceptable urine output for a 70 kg man, calculated based on standard physiological requirements to maintain renal function and prevent acute kidney injury.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe minimum acceptable urine output is a critical indicator of adequate renal perfusion and overall fluid status, especially in surgical patients. A general guideline is 0.5 mL/kg/hour. This rate ensures sufficient glomerular filtration to excrete metabolic waste products and maintain electrolyte balance. Below this threshold, patients are at increased risk for developing acute kidney injury (AKI) due to hypoperfusion or other renal insults, necessitating prompt intervention to optimize fluid status and hemodynamics.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 7 ml/hour is significantly below the minimum acceptable threshold and indicates severe oliguria or anuria, which is a medical emergency.\nOption B (Incorrect): 70 ml/hour is a normal to high urine output, well above the minimum acceptable level.\nOption D (Incorrect): 100 ml/hour is a high urine output, indicating good renal function and fluid status, not a minimum.\nOption E (Incorrect): 105 ml/hour is also a high urine output, far exceeding the minimum acceptable rate.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Urine Output Category | Rate (mL/kg/hour) | Rate for 70 kg man (mL/hour) |\n|-----------------------|-------------------|------------------------------|\n| Minimum Acceptable    | 0.5               | 35                           |\n| Normal                | 1.0 - 2.0         | 70 - 140                     |\n| Oliguria              | < 0.5             | < 35                         |\n| Anuria                | < 0.05            | < 3.5                        |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Minimum urine output is 0.5 mL/kg/hour; crucial for renal perfusion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring surgery, urine output is continuously monitored via a Foley catheter. A sudden drop below 0.5 mL/kg/hour should prompt immediate assessment of blood pressure, cardiac output, and fluid status, often visualized by changes in central venous pressure or arterial line waveforms.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKDIGO Clinical Practice Guideline for Acute Kidney Injury (2012): Defines AKI stages based on serum creatinine and urine output criteria, with oliguria being a key indicator.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 7 ml/ hour. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 70 ml/ hour. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 35 ml/ hour. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 100 ml/ hour. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | 105 ml/ hour. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
