  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Small bowel wakes up first, colon is the sleepyhead.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct sequence for the return of gastrointestinal motility after abdominal surgery is typically the small intestine first, followed by the stomach, and then the colon. This differential recovery is a well-established physiological phenomenon crucial for understanding postoperative ileus.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPostoperative ileus (POI) is a transient impairment of GI motility. The small intestine recovers fastest, often within hours, due to its intrinsic pacemaker activity and less susceptibility to sympathetic inhibition. The stomach typically recovers next, within 24-48 hours, while the colon, with its more complex innervation and greater sensitivity to sympathetic tone and inflammatory mediators, is the slowest to recover, often taking 3-5 days. This differential recovery is crucial for understanding POI management and patient recovery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): \"stomach, intestine, colon\" - The small intestine typically recovers before the stomach.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"colon, intestine, stomach\" - The colon is consistently the last segment to recover motility.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"colon, stomach, intestine\" - This order is incorrect as the colon is last and the small intestine is first.\nOption E (Incorrect): \"stomach, colon, intestine\" - This order is incorrect as the small intestine is first and the colon is last.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| GI Segment | Typical Recovery Time | Key Factors |\n|:-----------|:----------------------|:------------|\n| Small Intestine | Hours (6-12h) | Intrinsic pacemaker activity, less sympathetic inhibition |\n| Stomach | 24-48 hours | More susceptible to sympathetic inhibition than small bowel |\n| Colon | 3-5 days | Most sensitive to sympathetic inhibition, inflammatory mediators, opioids |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Small bowel first, stomach second, colon last for post-op motility.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn abdominal X-ray, prolonged ileus would show diffusely dilated loops of bowel with air-fluid levels, without a distinct transition point. Intraoperatively, one might observe a distended, atonic bowel.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEnhanced Recovery After Surgery (ERAS) Society Guidelines for Colorectal Surgery (2018) recommend early mobilization, early oral feeding, and opioid-sparing analgesia to minimize postoperative ileus.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | intestine, stomach, colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | stomach, intestine, colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | colon, intestine, stomach | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | colon, stomach, intestine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | stomach, colon, intestine | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
