  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Jejunum: where the bulk of your food becomes you.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe jejunum is the primary site for the absorption of the majority of digested nutrients, including carbohydrates, proteins, and fats. Its specialized structure maximizes this crucial function, making it the correct answer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe jejunum is anatomically and physiologically optimized for nutrient absorption. It features a large surface area due to its length, prominent plicae circulares (circular folds), villi, and microvilli, which collectively increase the absorptive surface by hundreds of times. This extensive surface, coupled with a rich blood supply and specialized transport mechanisms, allows for efficient uptake of most macronutrients and many micronutrients into the bloodstream.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Stomach) (Incorrect): The stomach's primary role is mechanical and chemical digestion, with very limited absorption (e.g., alcohol, some drugs).\nOption B (Duodenum) (Incorrect): While the duodenum is critical for initial digestion and absorption of specific nutrients like iron, calcium, and some vitamins, the *majority* of overall nutrient absorption occurs distally in the jejunum.\nOption D (Ileum) (Incorrect): The ileum is primarily responsible for absorbing vitamin B12 and bile salts, and some remaining nutrients, but not the *majority* of overall nutrient absorption.\nOption E (Colon) (Incorrect): The colon's main function is water and electrolyte absorption, and fermentation of undigested material, with negligible nutrient absorption.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| GI Segment | Primary Function | Key Absorbed Nutrients |\n|---|---|---|\n| Stomach | Digestion (protein, fat), mixing | Alcohol, some drugs |\n| Duodenum | Digestion, initial absorption | Iron, Calcium, Folate, some fats |\n| Jejunum | *Majority* of nutrient absorption | Carbohydrates, Proteins, Fats, Water-soluble vitamins |\n| Ileum | Specific absorption | Vitamin B12, Bile salts |\n| Colon | Water, Electrolyte absorption | Water, Electrolytes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Jejunum is the workhorse for nutrient absorption.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the jejunum can be identified by its thicker wall, more prominent plicae circulares (valvulae conniventes), and longer vasa recta compared to the ileum. It also has less mesenteric fat and fewer arterial arcades.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific society guideline directly addresses the primary site of nutrient absorption as it's fundamental physiology. However, guidelines for short bowel syndrome (e.g., ASPEN Clinical Guidelines for Nutrition Support of Hospitalized Adult Patients, 2016) implicitly rely on this knowledge.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Stomach | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Duodenum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Jejunum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Ileum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
