  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gut works? Feed it! PN is a last resort.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is that parenteral nutrition (PN) is less likely to cause diarrhea compared to enteral nutrition (EN). This is because PN bypasses the gastrointestinal tract entirely, avoiding direct gut-related side effects common with EN.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEnteral nutrition delivers nutrients directly into the GI tract, which is crucial for maintaining gut integrity, barrier function, and immunologic health. However, this direct delivery can also lead to complications such as diarrhea, often due to hyperosmolar formulas, rapid infusion rates, or intolerance to specific components. Parenteral nutrition, by contrast, delivers nutrients intravenously, completely bypassing the gut. While PN has its own significant complications, direct gut-related issues like diarrhea, which are common with EN, are less frequently or directly attributable to the PN itself.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Parenteral nutrition is significantly more expensive than enteral nutrition due to the cost of solutions, compounding, administration equipment, and intensive monitoring.\nOption B (Incorrect): Parenteral nutrition carries a higher risk of infectious complications, particularly catheter-related bloodstream infections, compared to enteral nutrition.\nOption C (Incorrect): Parenteral nutrition bypasses the gut, leading to disuse atrophy of the gut mucosa and impaired gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT) function, thus not preserving immunologic function.\nOption D (Incorrect): Long-term parenteral nutrition is associated with metabolic bone disease, including osteopenia and osteoporosis, due to various factors like nutrient imbalances and altered hormone metabolism.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Enteral Nutrition (EN) | Parenteral Nutrition (PN) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Cost** | Less expensive | More expensive |\n| **Infection Risk** | Lower (maintains gut barrier) | Higher (catheter-related sepsis) |\n| **Gut Function** | Preserves gut integrity & immunity | Gut atrophy, impaired immunity |\n| **Diarrhea** | Common (formula, rate, intolerance) | Less common (not directly gut-related) |\n| **Metabolic Bone Disease** | Rare | Common with long-term use |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: EN is always preferred over PN if the gut works; PN has more complications.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nN/A\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition (ASPEN) Clinical Guidelines for the Provision and Assessment of Nutrition Support Therapy in Adult Patients (2016). These guidelines emphasize the preference for enteral nutrition over parenteral nutrition whenever the gastrointestinal tract is functional, citing fewer complications and lower cost.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Is less expensive | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Has less infectious complications | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Preserves immunologic function of gut | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Is not associated with metabolic bone dysfunction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Is less likely to cause diarrhea | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
