  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 FeNa < 1%: Kidneys are thirsty, not broken!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. Postoperative oliguria with a fractional excretion of sodium (FeNa) less than 1% is the classic presentation of pre-renal acute kidney injury (AKI). This indicates that the kidneys are actively conserving sodium and water in response to decreased renal perfusion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPre-renal AKI occurs when there is inadequate blood flow to the kidneys, such as from hypovolemia, decreased cardiac output, or systemic vasodilation. The healthy kidney responds to this hypoperfusion by activating compensatory mechanisms like the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS) and antidiuretic hormone (ADH) release. These mechanisms lead to increased reabsorption of sodium and water in the renal tubules, resulting in a concentrated urine with very little sodium excretion, hence an FeNa less than 1%.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Intrinsic acute renal failure, particularly acute tubular necrosis (ATN), typically presents with a fractional excretion of sodium greater than 2% due to damage to the renal tubules, impairing their ability to reabsorb sodium.\nOption C (Incorrect): Chronic renal insufficiency is a long-standing condition and not typically characterized by acute postoperative oliguria with a specific FeNa value as the primary diagnostic feature. FeNa can be variable in chronic kidney disease.\nOption D (Incorrect): Acute tubular necrosis (ATN) is a common cause of intrinsic acute renal failure and, as such, is associated with a high FeNa (>2%) due to impaired tubular reabsorption.\nOption E (Incorrect): Obstructive uropathy (post-renal AKI) can initially present with a low FeNa if the kidney is still attempting to conserve volume, but as the obstruction persists and causes tubular damage, the FeNa can rise. Pre-renal AKI is the most consistent cause for FeNa < 1% in oliguria.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| AKI Type | FeNa | Urine Osmolality | Urine Sodium |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Pre-renal | < 1% | > 500 mOsm/kg | < 20 mEq/L |\n| Intrinsic (ATN) | > 2% | < 350 mOsm/kg | > 40 mEq/L |\n| Post-renal (early) | < 1% | > 500 mOsm/kg | < 20 mEq/L |\n| Post-renal (late) | > 2% | < 350 mOsm/kg | > 40 mEq/L |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Low FeNa means the kidney is trying to save sodium; think pre-renal.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor postoperative oliguria, a renal ultrasound is crucial to rule out obstructive uropathy, which would appear as hydronephrosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKidney Disease: Improving Global Outcomes (KDIGO) Clinical Practice Guideline for Acute Kidney Injury (2012) provides comprehensive recommendations for AKI diagnosis and management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pre renal acute renal failure. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Intrinsic acute renal failure. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Chronic renal insufficiency. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Acute tubular necrosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Obstructive uropathy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
