  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Time is tissue, especially in sepsis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nSepsis is a critical condition defined by a dysregulated host response to infection leading to life-threatening organ dysfunction. This question assesses knowledge of the Sepsis-3 definition and key management principles. The false statement incorrectly identifies the SOFA score threshold for organ dysfunction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Sepsis-3 definition, established in 2016, redefined sepsis as life-threatening organ dysfunction caused by a dysregulated host response to infection. Organ dysfunction is clinically identified by an acute change in the total SOFA score of ≥2 points due to the infection. This threshold is crucial as it correlates with an approximate 10% in-hospital mortality risk in general hospital patients with suspected infection, guiding early intervention and management strategies.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This statement is TRUE. It accurately reflects the Sepsis-3 definition of sepsis.\nOption B (Incorrect): This statement is TRUE. For patients without known pre-existing organ dysfunction, the baseline SOFA score is indeed assumed to be zero for calculating the acute change.\nOption D (Incorrect): This statement is TRUE. The Surviving Sepsis Campaign guidelines strongly recommend administering broad-spectrum antibiotics within one hour of sepsis recognition.\nOption E (Incorrect): This statement is TRUE. A SOFA score ≥2 in patients with suspected infection is associated with an approximate 10% in-hospital mortality risk.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Sepsis-3 Definition | Old Sepsis Definition (SIRS) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Definition** | Life-threatening organ dysfunction caused by a dysregulated host response to infection | Systemic Inflammatory Response Syndrome (SIRS) criteria + suspected infection |\n| **Organ Dysfunction** | Acute change in SOFA score ≥2 points | Not explicitly defined by a score, but by specific organ failures |\n| **Mortality Risk** | SOFA ≥2 associated with ~10% mortality | SIRS criteria alone did not predict mortality as well |\n| **Focus** | Host response and organ dysfunction | Inflammatory response |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sepsis-3: SOFA ≥2 for organ dysfunction, 1-hour antibiotics.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (e.g., CT, X-ray, ultrasound) is crucial in sepsis workup to identify the source of infection (e.g., abscess, pneumonia, pyelonephritis) and guide source control.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSurviving Sepsis Campaign Guidelines 2021. Recommends early recognition, rapid administration of antibiotics within 1 hour, and source control.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sepsis is defined as life-threatening organ dysfunction caused by a dysregu | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The baseline SOFA score can be assumed to be zero in patients not known to  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Organ dysfunction can be identified as an acute change in total SOFA(sequen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Management with Broad spectrum Antibiotic should be done within one hour of | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | SOFA score ≥2 reflects an overall mortality risk of approximately 10% in a  | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
