  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When C. diff strikes, oral vanc is the best bet!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct next step is to switch to oral vancomycin. This is the preferred first-line treatment for Clostridioides difficile infection due to its superior efficacy compared to metronidazole, especially in cases of moderate to severe disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOral vancomycin acts locally in the gastrointestinal tract, achieving high intraluminal concentrations that are bactericidal against C. difficile. Its poor systemic absorption ensures targeted action where the infection resides, minimizing systemic side effects. This targeted delivery is crucial for eradicating the toxin-producing bacteria and resolving the pseudomembranous colitis characteristic of C. difficile infection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (start metronidazole therapy) (Incorrect): While metronidazole can be used for non-severe C. diff, oral vancomycin or fidaxomicin are superior in efficacy and are recommended as first-line agents. Metronidazole has lower cure rates and higher recurrence rates compared to vancomycin.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| C. diff Severity | Definition | First-line Treatment |\n|---|---|---|\n| Non-severe | WBC < 15,000 and Cr < 1.5x baseline | Oral Vancomycin 125 mg QID x 10 days OR Oral Fidaxomicin 200 mg BID x 10 days |\n| Severe | WBC >= 15,000 OR Cr >= 1.5x baseline | Oral Vancomycin 125 mg QID x 10 days OR Oral Fidaxomicin 200 mg BID x 10 days |\n| Fulminant | Hypotension, ileus, megacolon | Oral Vancomycin 500 mg QID (with rectal if ileus) + IV Metronidazole 500 mg TID + Surgical consult |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Oral vancomycin is the preferred first-line treatment for C. diff, regardless of severity.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable as no imaging was provided in the question. Diagnosis is clinical and laboratory-based.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInfectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) 2021 Clinical Practice Guidelines for Clostridioides difficile Infection in Adults and Children. These guidelines recommend oral vancomycin or fidaxomicin as first-line treatment for initial C. difficile infection, regardless of severity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Switch to oral vancomycin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | start metronidazole therapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
