  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Medial is lacunar, lateral is vein, don't get them mixed up!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the incorrect statement regarding the femoral canal. Option D is the correct answer because it incorrectly states that the lacunar ligament forms the lateral border of the femoral canal; it actually forms the medial border.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe femoral canal is the most medial compartment of the femoral sheath, a critical anatomical space in the groin. Understanding its precise boundaries is essential for diagnosing and repairing femoral hernias. The lacunar ligament, also known as Gimbernat's ligament, forms the sharp, crescent-shaped medial boundary of the femoral ring, which is the superior opening of the femoral canal. Laterally, the femoral vein forms the boundary, separating the canal from the vascular compartment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This statement is actually correct. The inguinal ligament forms the superior boundary of the femoral ring, which is the entrance to the femoral canal.\nOption B (Incorrect): This statement is actually correct. The pectineus muscle and its fascia, overlying the pectineal line of the pubis, form the posterior boundary of the femoral canal.\nOption C (Incorrect): This statement is actually correct. The femoral canal typically contains loose areolar tissue, lymphatic vessels, and often a deep inguinal lymph node (Cloquet's node).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Boundary of Femoral Ring/Canal | Structure |\n| :----------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------ |\n| Superior                       | Inguinal ligament                                 |\n| Medial                         | Lacunar ligament (Gimbernat's ligament)           |\n| Lateral                        | Femoral vein                                      |\n| Posterior                      | Pectineus muscle and fascia (over pectineal line) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lacunar ligament is medial, femoral vein is lateral to the femoral canal.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring open hernia repair, the lacunar ligament is a key landmark forming the sharp medial edge of the femoral ring. It can be palpated and sometimes needs to be incised (carefully, to avoid the external iliac vein) to reduce a tightly incarcerated femoral hernia. On cross-sectional imaging (CT/MRI), the femoral canal appears as a small fat-filled space medial to the femoral vein, bounded by the inguinal ligament superiorly and the pectineus muscle posteriorly.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nN/A\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Inguinal ligament is the superior border of femoral canal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pectinular line posterioly to femoral canal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Contains lymph Nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | lacunar ligament is the lateral border | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
