  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't give antibiotics for benign boob goo!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nProphylactic antibiotics are not routinely indicated for the management of duct ectasia itself, nor are they as strongly indicated for surgical excision of duct ectasia compared to hernia repair or colectomy. The primary goal of surgical prophylaxis is to prevent surgical site infections (SSIs) in procedures with a higher risk of contamination or those involving foreign bodies.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuct ectasia is a benign, non-infectious condition of the breast ducts. While surgical excision (microdochectomy) may be performed for symptomatic relief, it is typically classified as a clean or clean-contaminated procedure. In contrast, hernioplasty/herniorrhaphy, especially with mesh, and colectomy, which involves opening the gastrointestinal tract, carry a significantly higher risk of bacterial contamination and subsequent surgical site infection, thus mandating prophylactic antibiotic use.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption a (Hernioplasty) (Incorrect): Prophylactic antibiotics are generally indicated for hernioplasty, especially when mesh is used, due to the presence of a foreign body and the potential for surgical site infection.\nOption b (Herniorrhaphy) (Incorrect): Similar to hernioplasty, prophylactic antibiotics are typically indicated for herniorrhaphy to reduce the risk of surgical site infection.\nOption d (Colectomy) (Incorrect): Colectomy is a clean-contaminated procedure involving the bowel, which is heavily colonized with bacteria. Prophylactic antibiotics are universally indicated and crucial for preventing severe surgical site infections and anastomotic leaks.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure Type | SSI Risk | Prophylactic Antibiotic Indication | Common Antibiotic Choice |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Colectomy | High (Clean-Contaminated) | Strongly Indicated | Cefoxitin, Cefazolin + Metronidazole |\n| Hernioplasty/Herniorrhaphy (with mesh) | Moderate (Clean/Clean-Contaminated with implant) | Indicated | Cefazolin |\n| Breast Surgery (e.g., microdochectomy for duct ectasia) | Low-Moderate (Clean/Clean-Contaminated) | Often considered, but less universally mandated than bowel surgery; may be omitted for short, clean cases | Cefazolin |\n| Uncomplicated Duct Ectasia (non-surgical) | N/A | Not Indicated | N/A |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Prophylaxis targets contamination risk; benign, non-infectious conditions rarely need it.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, duct ectasia may present as dilated, thickened ducts, sometimes filled with inspissated material or appearing inflamed. Imaging (mammogram, ultrasound) may show dilated ducts, calcifications, or a mass, but the question does not contain an image.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) and Surgical Infection Society (SIS) Guidelines for Antimicrobial Prophylaxis in Surgery (e.g., 2017/2024 updates). These guidelines provide detailed recommendations for specific surgical procedures, strongly recommending prophylaxis for colorectal surgery and hernia repair with mesh, while offering more nuanced guidance for breast surgery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | Hernioplasty | ❌ Incorrect |\n| b | Herniorrhaphy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| c | Duct ectasia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| d | Colectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
