  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fluid balance: a delicate dance, especially in tiny humans.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 1200 ml. This is derived from the Holliday-Segar formula for maintenance fluid, adjusted for the infant's fever. Accurate fluid management is critical in pediatric patients to prevent dehydration or fluid overload.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Holliday-Segar formula dictates 100 ml/kg/day for the first 10 kg of body weight. For a 10 kg infant, this equates to 1000 ml/day. Additionally, fever increases metabolic rate and insensible fluid losses. A general rule of thumb is to add 10-12% for every degree Celsius above 37°C. With a temperature of 38°C (1°C above normal), an additional 10-12% (100-120 ml) is required, bringing the total to approximately 1100-1120 ml, which rounds up to 1200 ml among the given options.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption a (300 ml) (Incorrect): This volume is significantly too low for a 10 kg infant and would lead to severe dehydration.\nOption b (500 ml) (Incorrect): This volume is also far too low for maintenance fluid requirements and would result in dehydration.\nOption c (800 ml) (Incorrect): While closer, 800 ml is still insufficient for a 10 kg infant, especially with a fever, and would not meet daily fluid needs.\nOption e (1500 ml) (Incorrect): This volume is excessively high for a 10 kg infant and could lead to fluid overload, electrolyte disturbances, and potentially pulmonary edema.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Weight Range | Maintenance Fluid (Holliday-Segar) | Fever Adjustment (per °C > 37°C) | Clinical Implication |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| First 10 kg | 100 ml/kg/day | Add 10-12% | Prevents dehydration, supports metabolic needs |\n| 11-20 kg | 1000 ml + 50 ml/kg for each kg > 10 kg | Add 10-12% | Balances fluid and electrolyte homeostasis |\n| > 20 kg | 1500 ml + 20 ml/kg for each kg > 20 kg | Add 10-12% | Avoids fluid overload in larger children/adults |\n| Insensible Losses | ~400-500 ml/day (adults) | Increased with fever, tachypnea | Must be accounted for in total fluid calculation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Holliday-Segar + 10-12% per degree Celsius for fever.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable for this question as it is a calculation-based fluid management scenario. No imaging or intraoperative findings are relevant.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Dehydration in Children (2018). Recommends using Holliday-Segar for maintenance fluid calculation and adjusting for clinical conditions like fever.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | 300 ml | ❌ Incorrect |\n| b | 500 ml | ❌ Incorrect |\n| c | 800 ml | ❌ Incorrect |\n| d | 1200 ml | ❌ Incorrect |\n| e | 1500 ml | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
