  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Keep the knee, keep the stride.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT because the question asks for the EXCEPT statement, and option A incorrectly states that energy expenditure is lower following above-knee amputation (AKA) compared to below-knee amputation (BKA). In reality, preserving the knee joint in BKA significantly reduces the energy required for ambulation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPreserving the knee joint in a below-knee amputation is biomechanically advantageous. The knee acts as a crucial lever and shock absorber, allowing for more natural gait mechanics, better prosthetic control, and reduced compensatory movements from the hip and trunk. This translates to significantly less oxygen consumption and cardiovascular strain during ambulation compared to an above-knee amputation, where the prosthetic knee joint requires active control and greater energy input, making ambulation much more demanding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Emergency amputations are often performed in critically ill patients with sepsis, severe trauma, or uncontrolled infection, leading to higher rates of complications, re-amputation, and mortality compared to planned, elective procedures.\nOption C (Incorrect): Specialist surgeons, particularly those with high volume experience in amputation surgery, demonstrate improved patient outcomes due to refined surgical techniques, better limb shaping, and comprehensive perioperative care, which optimizes prosthetic fitting and rehabilitation potential.\nOption D (Incorrect): Diabetes is a leading cause of major lower limb amputations due to its associated complications like peripheral neuropathy, peripheral artery disease, and increased susceptibility to infection, all contributing to non-healing wounds and critical limb ischemia.\nOption E (Incorrect): Major surgery, especially involving the lower extremities and often accompanied by prolonged immobility, creates a hypercoagulable state and venous stasis, significantly increasing the risk of deep vein thrombosis and subsequent pulmonary embolism.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Below-Knee Amputation (BKA) | Above-Knee Amputation (AKA) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Knee Joint** | Preserved | Lost |\n| **Energy Expenditure for Ambulation** | Lower (approx. 10-40% above normal) | Higher (approx. 60-100% above normal) |\n| **Prosthetic Control** | Easier, more natural gait | More complex, requires greater effort |\n| **Rehabilitation Potential** | Generally better functional outcomes | More challenging, higher rates of non-ambulation |\n| **Residual Limb Length** | Longer, better lever arm | Shorter, less leverage |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Preserve the knee, preserve the energy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPreoperative imaging (e.g., angiography, CT angiography) is crucial to assess vascular supply and determine the optimal amputation level for healing. Intraoperatively, meticulous surgical technique is paramount, including careful muscle and nerve handling, creation of a well-padded residual limb, and achieving primary closure without tension to optimize prosthetic fitting and minimize complications.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Patients with Critical Limb Ischemia (2016) recommends a multidisciplinary approach and emphasizes limb salvage where possible, but also discusses principles of amputation when necessary, including level selection for optimal function.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Energy expenditure to achieve mobility is lower following above knee amputa | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Patient outcome is worse following emergency amputation than elective amput | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Amputations performed by specialist surgeons have improved outcomes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Compared to the general population, patients with diabetes are at higher ri | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Deep vein thrombosis is a recognized risk following major amputation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 829487955-General-Rotation.txt**\n",
